etymologies: early 16th century; earliest use found in Thomas Paynell (d. ?1564), translator. From enter + -er

definitions: A person who (or occasionally a thing which) goes or comes into a place, situation, etc. Formerly also occasionally with in.
A person who records or submits something, especially in writing; one who adds to a register, database, etc.

notes.text: Now chiefly with reference to electronic data, especially in data enterer.

definitions: An entrant in a race, contest, competition, etc.
